  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - An intergovernmental organization that sets global standards for preventing money laundering\n\n2. The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC)\n\n3. The International Monetary Fund (IMF) guidelines on anti-money laundering\n\n4. The Bank Secrecy Act and USA PATRIOT Act in the United States\n\n5. The European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal control systems\n- Cooperate with law enforcement investigations\n\nMost countries have their own national laws implementing these international standards, with penalties for non-compliance.",
